One possible reason why there are so many variations is that UNIX is a
registered trademark of AT&amp;T.  It may be a violation of trademark law
to say in an HINFO field that your machine runs "UNIX".  (It may not,
I'm not a lawyer.  But they keep drilling into me that you have to say
it's a trademark, use it as an adjective modifying a product, etc.)
This is in fact the reason why names like Xenix, SunOS, AIX, and so on
are the product names - AT&amp;T won't let them call their product UNIX.
(The upcoming venture with Microsoft will be the first.)

Before pushing people to standardize on the name "UNIX" it might be
worthwhile having a DARPA attorney contact an AT&amp;T attorney to get
the facts straight.

Maybe it would be safer to call them POSIX, I'll bet IEEE won't mind.

	Mark

